column5: \begin{aligned}Yes—geometrically, the arc‐length formula in 3D is a continuous version of the Pythagorean theorem applied to infinitesimal line segments.\\\text{Let }\mathbf{r}(t)=(x(t),\,y(t),\,z(t)),\,t\in[a,b].\\\text{Partition }[a,b]\colon a=t_0<\cdots<t_n=b.\\\Delta s_i=\|\mathbf{r}(t_i)-\mathbf{r}(t_{i-1})\|=\sqrt{[x(t_i)-x(t_{i-1})]^2+[y(t_i)-y(t_{i-1})]^2+[z(t_i)-z(t_{i-1})]^2}.\\\Delta s_i\approx\sqrt{[x'(t_{i-1})\Delta t_i]^2+[y'(t_{i-1})\Delta t_i]^2+[z'(t_{i-1})\Delta t_i]^2}=\sqrt{(x')^2+(y')^2+(z')^2}\big|_{t_{i-1}}\Delta t_i.\\L=\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{i=1}^n\Delta s_i=\int_a^b\sqrt{[x'(t)]^2+[y'(t)]^2+[z'(t)]^2}\,dt=\int_a^b\|\mathbf{r}'(t)\|\,dt.\end{aligned}
